This line chart shows regional population data from 1950 to 2100. The x-axis shows years in 20-year steps; the y-axis shows population size (millions, M, to billions, G).

It is clear to see that Asia (the orange line) has the largest population, which is projected to peak a little above 5 billion around mid-century (~2050–2060) and then to decline to about 4.6 billion.

Africa (blue) shows the strongest growth—rising from a few hundred million in 1950 to almost 4 billion by 2100—almost closing the gap to Asia.
